1
00:00:01,120 --> 00:00:02,560
Six Minute English.

2
00:00:02,560 --> 00:00:05,799
From bbclearningenglish.com.

3
00:00:06,680 --> 00:00:10,960
Hello and welcome to Six Minute English from BBC Learning English.

4
00:00:10,960 --> 00:00:11,840
I'm Pippa.

5
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:12,999
And I'm Beth.

6
00:00:13,055 --> 00:00:16,735
Have you ever been scared of speaking in English?

7
00:00:16,654 --> 00:00:22,895
In this episode, we're talking about why speaking in a foreign language can be so stressful.

8
00:00:22,895 --> 00:00:27,295
So Pippa, do you ever get nervous speaking in a different language?

9
00:00:27,610 --> 00:00:28,529
Yes.

10
00:00:28,529 --> 00:00:33,870
I learned French when I was younger and I was actually quite good at it, I think.

11
00:00:33,870 --> 00:00:37,250
But I was really nervous when I was speaking French.

12
00:00:37,250 --> 00:00:38,129
How about you?

13
00:00:38,129 --> 00:00:38,530
Yeah.

14
00:00:38,530 --> 00:00:40,690
I've always felt like that with Spanish.

15
00:00:40,690 --> 00:00:47,775
I am scared to speak because I don't want to make mistakes even though I know it's okay to make mistakes.

16
00:00:47,775 --> 00:00:50,635
Well, in this episode of six Minute English,

17
00:00:50,635 --> 00:00:54,835
we'll be hearing about how to feel less nervous when you speak English.

18
00:00:54,754 --> 00:00:58,355
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases.

19
00:00:58,410 --> 00:01:04,789
You can practise these with the quiz and worksheets on our website bbclearningenglish.com.

20
00:01:04,789 --> 00:01:08,229
But first, I have a question for you, Pippa.

21
00:01:08,229 --> 00:01:11,850
So English has around 1,000,000 words.

22
00:01:11,770 --> 00:01:19,245
But on average, how many words does a typical English speaker use in daily conversation?

23
00:01:19,405 --> 00:01:32,239
Is it a between 2,003, b between 20,030, or c between 200,300.

24
00:01:32,239 --> 00:01:35,920
I'm gonna say a 2,000 to 3,000.

25
00:01:35,920 --> 00:01:36,399
Okay.

26
00:01:36,399 --> 00:01:39,160
Well, we will find out later in the program.

27
00:01:39,400 --> 00:01:46,305
Now, Pepe, you said you found it stressful speaking in French even though you are quite good at it.

28
00:01:46,305 --> 00:01:50,365
Now someone else who has had this experience is Hanan Razek.

29
00:01:50,365 --> 00:01:58,479
Hanan is a journalist at BBC Arabic and also host of the podcast Beating Speaking Anxiety.

30
00:01:58,400 --> 00:02:03,880
Here she is telling BBC Learning English presenter Georgie about speaking English.

31
00:02:03,880 --> 00:02:06,140
My English was actually pretty good.

32
00:02:06,140 --> 00:02:09,919
But having conversations with people, I found it really difficult.

33
00:02:10,045 --> 00:02:12,325
So when I first joined the BBC,

34
00:02:12,325 --> 00:02:16,004
the Learning English team made an assessment of my English level,

35
00:02:16,004 --> 00:02:21,644
which they used to do for all new joiners to see if they need any help or courses.

36
00:02:21,725 --> 00:02:24,525
My results were pretty good and I was fluent.

37
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:26,900
But on that very same day,

38
00:02:26,900 --> 00:02:29,560
leaving the building and going to get some coffee,

39
00:02:29,560 --> 00:02:32,720
I couldn't really understand what the barista was saying.

40
00:02:32,640 --> 00:02:34,999
And I felt pretty nervous to order coffee

41
00:02:34,999 --> 00:02:38,935
and was trying to stress every single word hoping

42
00:02:38,935 --> 00:02:42,614
that my grammar is correct and I am pronouncing the words right.

43
00:02:42,614 --> 00:02:42,935
Yeah.

44
00:02:42,935 --> 00:02:45,935
I'm sure that's a situation lots of people can relate to.

45
00:02:45,935 --> 00:02:49,274
Hanan's results on her English assessment were pretty good,

46
00:02:49,274 --> 00:02:52,469
but she was still pretty nervous to speak in English,

47
00:02:52,469 --> 00:02:55,470
for example, when ordering a coffee in English.

48
00:02:55,390 --> 00:02:58,830
The modifier pretty means quite or a bit.

49
00:02:58,750 --> 00:03:03,869
Georgie says that Hanan's experience is something that lots of people can relate to.

50
00:03:04,085 --> 00:03:06,265
If you relate to a situation,

51
00:03:06,265 --> 00:03:08,145
you know what it feels like,

52
00:03:08,145 --> 00:03:11,445
usually because a similar thing has happened to you.

53
00:03:11,605 --> 00:03:17,924
So lots of people feel nervous speaking another language even if they're good at it, like an an.

54
00:03:18,070 --> 00:03:20,929
We can call this speaking anxiety.

55
00:03:20,929 --> 00:03:27,370
Anxiety means an uncomfortable feeling or worry about something that is happening or could happen in the future.

56
00:03:27,370 --> 00:03:33,030
So why do so many people have anxiety about speaking a foreign language?

57
00:03:33,315 --> 00:03:38,115
Experts think it's connected to the beliefs we have about ourselves.

58
00:03:38,195 --> 00:03:43,447
Han Luo, professor of Chinese at Lafayette College in The United States, 

59
00:03:43,447 --> 00:03:47,420
explains more to BBC Learning English presenter Georgie.

60
00:03:47,420 --> 00:03:50,559
You know, usually, the beliefs that cause anxiety,

61
00:03:50,559 --> 00:03:55,400
especially severe anxiety, are, we call it irrational beliefs

62
00:03:55,880 --> 00:04:00,359
and also, like, some low self perceptions,

63
00:04:01,315 --> 00:04:08,195
fear of negative evaluation, all those learner internal, you know, factors.

64
00:04:08,675 --> 00:04:14,195
And Hans says that learners worry about mistakes because they're scared of negative evaluation.

65
00:04:14,340 --> 00:04:19,299
In other words, that people will judge them for their mistakes and think badly of them.

66
00:04:19,459 --> 00:04:23,160
Han argues that irrational beliefs can make us anxious.

67
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:27,080
Irrational beliefs are beliefs that aren't based on things that are true.

68
00:04:27,080 --> 00:04:28,260
They're not logical.

69
00:04:28,325 --> 00:04:33,925
Han says some people who have speaking anxiety have low self perceptions.

70
00:04:33,844 --> 00:04:37,145
Your self perception is what you think about yourself.

71
00:04:37,145 --> 00:04:41,765
Self perception and irrational beliefs are both internal factors.

72
00:04:41,810 --> 00:04:45,870
They come from inside your head, not from the people around you.

73
00:04:45,870 --> 00:04:51,950
So for example, when you speak your first language, you might feel confident and intelligent.

74
00:04:51,950 --> 00:04:56,850
But when you speak in a new language, you make mistakes and feel less confident.

75
00:04:56,885 --> 00:05:01,365
You can't show people what you're really like and this is frustrating.

76
00:05:01,525 --> 00:05:07,085
But as we tell people all the time at BBC Learning English, mistakes are normal.

77
00:05:07,085 --> 00:05:10,165
You have to try to speak even though you make mistakes.

78
00:05:10,239 --> 00:05:12,200
And mistakes can be a good thing.

79
00:05:12,200 --> 00:05:13,760
They can help us learn.

80
00:05:13,679 --> 00:05:20,180
And if you want more tips to improve your speaking, listen to the Beating Speaking Anxiety podcast.

81
00:05:20,180 --> 00:05:22,800
There's a link in the notes below this episode.

82
00:05:23,054 --> 00:05:26,595
But Beth, I think it's time for the answer to your quiz question.

83
00:05:26,595 --> 00:05:27,415
Yes.

84
00:05:27,415 --> 00:05:33,855
I asked you how many words does the average English speaker use in daily communication?

85
00:05:34,015 --> 00:05:37,774
The answer is 20 to 30,000.

86
00:05:37,950 --> 00:05:39,110
That's quite a lot.

87
00:05:39,110 --> 00:05:39,429
Yeah.

88
00:05:39,429 --> 00:05:40,390
That's loads.

89
00:05:40,390 --> 00:05:41,190
Okay.

90
00:05:41,190 --> 00:05:44,090
Let's recap the vocabulary we've learnt.

91
00:05:44,090 --> 00:05:48,590
Pretty can be used as a modifier to mean quite or a bit.

92
00:05:48,590 --> 00:05:55,255
If you relate to a person or situation, you understand them, usually because you've experienced something similar.

93
00:05:55,255 --> 00:06:02,195
Anxiety is feeling uncomfortable or worried about something that is happening or could happen in the future.

94
00:06:02,275 --> 00:06:06,075
Irrational beliefs are beliefs about something that is not true.

95
00:06:06,075 --> 00:06:07,315
They're not logical.

96
00:06:07,450 --> 00:06:10,570
Self perception is the way you see yourself.

97
00:06:10,570 --> 00:06:13,970
And internal means inside the body or mind.

98
00:06:13,970 --> 00:06:16,610
Once again, our six minutes are up.

99
00:06:16,610 --> 00:06:20,270
But if you'd like to find out more about speaking anxiety,

100
00:06:20,270 --> 00:06:28,135
then head over to our website bbclearningenglish.com to find our beating speaking anxiety series.

101
00:06:28,054 --> 00:06:33,315
There are podcasts about the things we find scary when speaking a different language,

102
00:06:33,315 --> 00:06:37,095
and videos with tips to help you feel more confident with speaking.

103
00:06:37,030 --> 00:06:39,230
Thanks for joining us and goodbye.

104
00:06:39,230 --> 00:06:39,990
Goodbye.

105
00:06:40,789 --> 00:06:42,430
Six Minute English.

106
00:06:42,430 --> 00:06:45,150
From bbclearningenglish.com.
